From: 4noha
Subject: dwmmc: power-cycle SDIO device (bwfm WiFi) on resume
License: ISC (this patch modifies OpenBSD source and inherits ISC; see ../LICENSE-ISC)

dwmmc: power-cycle SDIO device (bwfm WiFi) on resume.

NOTE: superseded by dwmmc-resume-full-cycle.diff. Kept in-tree as the
first step in the chain because it was the patch actually deployed on
the v2 working kernel and because the diagnostic story below explains
WHY the full-cycle variant exists. If applying the modern stack,
prefer dwmmc-resume-full-cycle.diff and skip this one.

Problem (2026-06-02, DM250 / rk3128):
  After suspend/resume the WiFi chip stops responding:
    bwfm0 detached
    bwfm0 at sdmmc1 function 1
    bwfm_sdio_buf_read: error 60        <- errno 60 = ETIMEDOUT
  -> chip not answering on SDIO after resume. ifconfig down/up does
  not recover it.

Root cause:
  dwmmc_activate(DVACT_RESUME) re-initialised host state (clock,
  reset, host_reset, bus params) only and never power-cycled the
  attached SDIO device (the WiFi chip). The chip lost state across
  suspend, so when config_activate_children() runs bwfm's re-attach
  the firmware-load SDIO transfers ETIMEDOUT. dwmmc_bus_power() only
  runs the pwrseq on an sc_vdd 0 -> on transition, but at this point
  sc_vdd still holds the pre-suspend voltage and the pwrseq is
  skipped there too.

Fix:
  In DVACT_RESUME explicitly call dwmmc_pwrseq_pre / post (the
  mmc-pwrseq is the WiFi WL_REG_ON line) to power-cycle the chip
  before the child re-attaches.

Target: sys/dev/fdt/dwmmc.c::dwmmc_activate()

--- sys/dev/fdt/dwmmc.c.orig
+++ sys/dev/fdt/dwmmc.c
@@ dwmmc_activate(struct device *self, int act)
 	switch (act) {
 	case DVACT_RESUME:
 		/* dwmmc_host_reset will clobber these */
 		bus_width = sc->sc_bus_width;
 		bus_freq = sc->sc_bus_freq;
 		bus_timing = sc->sc_bus_timing;

 		clock_enable_all(sc->sc_node);
 		reset_deassert_all(sc->sc_node);
+
+		/*
+		 * The attached SDIO device (e.g. bwfm(4) WiFi) lost power
+		 * across suspend.  dwmmc_bus_power() only runs the pwrseq on a
+		 * 0->on sc_vdd transition, but sc_vdd still holds the
+		 * pre-suspend voltage here, so the child's re-attach finds the
+		 * chip unresponsive (bwfm_sdio_buf_read: error 60 == ETIMEDOUT).
+		 * Power-cycle the chip via its pwrseq reset-gpios so the
+		 * re-attach below (config_activate_children) succeeds.
+		 */
+		if (sc->sc_pwrseq) {
+			dwmmc_pwrseq_pre(sc->sc_pwrseq);
+			dwmmc_pwrseq_post(sc->sc_pwrseq);
+		}
+
 		dwmmc_host_reset(sc);

 		if (bus_width)
 			dwmmc_bus_width(sc, bus_width);
 		if (bus_freq)
 			dwmmc_bus_clock(sc, bus_freq, bus_timing);
 		break;
 	}

 	return config_activate_children(self, act);

Notes:
  - dwmmc_pwrseq_pre / post safely no-op when phandle == 0; the
    sc_pwrseq guard above is belt-and-braces.
  - pwrseq_post delay()s for post-power-on-delay-ms from DT. If the
    pre -> post gap is too short for the chip to become visible, add a
    delay(10000) (10 ms) between pre and post.
  - Upstream PR candidate: the generic dwmmc resume path skipping
    pwrseq could bite other SDIO-WiFi boards too.
